00:24:31.678 --> 00:24:32.471
Thank you.

529
00:24:34.514 --> 00:24:36.516
around the country
and we can host dinners

530
00:24:36.600 --> 00:24:37.893
of Republicans and Democrats.

531
00:24:37.976 --> 00:24:39.227
and if we can just get people
to sit down

532
00:24:39.311 --> 00:24:41.730
at a table together.
they'll realize

533
00:24:41.813 --> 00:24:45.692
that they're a lot more alike
than they thought.

534
00:24:45.775 --> 00:24:47.194
All right. welcome.

535
00:24:47.235 --> 00:24:49.237
We already kind of
welcomed you already.

536
00:24:49.321 --> 00:24:52.073
but I think the first thing
is to admit

537
00:24:52.157 --> 00:24:54.242
this is weird. right?

538
00:24:54.326 --> 00:24:57.078
One question I would love
to just sort of kick off

539
00:24:57.162 --> 00:25:01.875
is. like. what is your. um.

540
00:25:01.917 --> 00:25:04.085
your American story?

541
00:25:04.169 --> 00:25:07.047
Our theory
that divisions in America

542
00:25:07.130 --> 00:25:09.174
are rooted in politics

543
00:25:09.216 --> 00:25:12.052
got completely blown up
on Day One.

544
00:25:12.093 --> 00:25:14.804
Being called "illegal"
and being called a "wetback"

545
00:25:14.888 --> 00:25:17.807
and. you know.
every time I hear them.

546
00:25:17.891 --> 00:25:21.186
it's--it's dehumanizing.

547
00:25:21.228 --> 00:25:23.730
We learned very quickly
that our political divisions

548
00:25:23.813 --> 00:25:25.732
are more symptomatic
of something

549
00:25:25.815 --> 00:25:27.984
that goes a lot deeper.

550
00:25:28.068 --> 00:25:30.320
There's a huge division
in our country right now

551
00:25:30.403 --> 00:25:32.531
and. yeah. we wanted
to maybe see if we could

552
00:25:32.572 --> 00:25:34.908
start a little bit
of a conversation

553
00:25:34.950 --> 00:25:37.786
to try and break down
some walls of division.

554
00:25:37.869 --> 00:25:41.873
Generally speaking. um.

555
00:25:41.915 --> 00:25:45.085
I'd have to honestly say
that I don't have

556
00:25:45.126 --> 00:25:48.421
a really great feeling
towards white people.

557
00:25:48.505 --> 00:25:53.176
Um. a lot of it is because of
some of my experiences

558
00:25:53.260 --> 00:25:56.429
and some of what I've seen
my parents experience.

559
00:25:56.513 --> 00:25:59.599
I went into labor
with my first child

560
00:25:59.683 --> 00:26:02.227
when I was seven months along.

561
00:26:02.269 --> 00:26:05.480
and my water broke while I was
walking around the mall

562
00:26:05.564 --> 00:26:06.606
with my dad.

563
00:26:06.690 --> 00:26:08.733
He was buying baby clothes.

564
00:26:08.775 --> 00:26:11.111
And I went to the hospital.

565
00:26:11.194 --> 00:26:13.154
The nurse came in. and I said.

566
00:26:13.238 --> 00:26:14.781
"I think I'm having
contractions."

567
00:26:14.864 --> 00:26:17.659
and she examined me
very quickly and she said.

568
00:26:17.742 --> 00:26:19.619
"Oh. you're not ready
to have this baby yet.

569
00:26:19.661 --> 00:26:21.079
You call me back in here
when you're ready

570
00:26:21.121 --> 00:26:22.455
to have this baby."

571
00:26:22.497 --> 00:26:25.625
And they let me lay there
for hours.

572
00:26:25.709 --> 00:26:28.878
By the time the doctor came.
I was crowning.

573
00:26:28.962 --> 00:26:32.465
-Wow.
-And my first baby died.

574
00:26:32.549 --> 00:26:36.469
and I know that they did not
give me the care

575
00:26:36.511 --> 00:26:38.680
and the attention
that I deserved.

576
00:26:38.763 --> 00:26:42.809
I lost my baby
because they did not provide

577
00:26:42.892 --> 00:26:45.687
proper care for me.

578
00:26:45.770 --> 00:26:47.439
I'm so sorry.

579
00:26:48.982 --> 00:26:52.027
And it's so hard

580
00:26:52.110 --> 00:26:56.990
to know that I'm a good person.
I'm a good mother.

581
00:26:57.032 --> 00:26:59.784
and to have someone look at me

582
00:26:59.826 --> 00:27:03.038
or to look at Black children
as if they're criminals.

583
00:27:03.121 --> 00:27:05.206
as if we don't deserve
to be respected.

584
00:27:05.290 --> 00:27:08.126
we don't deserve
to be treated fairly.

585
00:27:08.168 --> 00:27:12.088
it does something to you
mentally and spiritually

586
00:27:12.172 --> 00:27:14.215
and emotionally.

587
00:27:14.299 --> 00:27:18.178
I've never forgotten
losing my first child

588
00:27:18.219 --> 00:27:22.766
because I was
a Black unwed mother.

589
00:27:22.849 --> 00:27:25.602
and they didn't think
that my child's life

590
00:27:25.685 --> 00:27:29.189
was as important
as the child being delivered

591
00:27:29.230 --> 00:27:31.691
in the room next to me.

592
00:27:33.276 --> 00:27:35.570
Mechelle. I'm so sorry.

593
00:27:35.654 --> 00:27:36.905
Stand up.

594
00:27:36.988 --> 00:27:40.116
(crying)

595
00:27:45.121 --> 00:27:47.332
Nothing can make it right.

596
00:27:48.875 --> 00:27:51.002
-It still hurts.
-I know.

597
00:27:51.044 --> 00:27:53.546
I know it does.
I'm so sorry.

598
00:27:55.382 --> 00:28:05.308
♪

599
00:28:07.143 --> 00:28:10.480
Beneath what we call
"political polarization"

600
00:28:10.563 --> 00:28:12.732
are a lot of other
fundamental tensions

601
00:28:12.774 --> 00:28:14.401
in our culture:

602
00:28:14.442 --> 00:28:16.361
race. religious differences.

603
00:28:16.403 --> 00:28:20.073
economic differences.
gender issues.

604
00:28:20.156 --> 00:28:23.910
Division is a human problem.
not just an American problem.

605
00:28:23.952 --> 00:28:25.286
♪

606
00:28:25.370 --> 00:28:26.830
If we're going to be
a democracy.

607
00:28:26.913 --> 00:28:29.207
we have to recognize our rights
and the rights of others

608
00:28:29.249 --> 00:28:31.459
and work through
the differences.

609
00:28:31.543 --> 00:28:34.921
That's our responsibility.

610
00:28:34.963 --> 00:28:44.723
♪

611
00:28:44.764 --> 00:28:49.644
Jazz is inherently
a call-and-response art form.

612
00:28:49.728 --> 00:28:50.979
♪

613
00:28:51.062 --> 00:28:52.772
The most important skill
is to listen.

614
00:28:52.856 --> 00:28:53.773
We have a special guest up here.

615
00:28:57.569 --> 00:28:59.904
(unintelligible)

616
00:28:59.946 --> 00:29:03.867
♪

617
00:29:03.950 --> 00:29:07.162
Imagine if we had a real
call-and-response in Congress

618
00:29:07.245 --> 00:29:09.247
where people would listen
and then respond

619
00:29:09.289 --> 00:29:11.374
with their ideas.

620
00:29:11.458 --> 00:29:15.128
♪

621
00:29:15.211 --> 00:29:18.047
That fusion of ideas
is what creates

622
00:29:18.131 --> 00:29:20.633
a stronger country.

623
00:29:20.675 --> 00:29:27.474
♪

