626
00:29:32.437 --> 00:29:34.230
and we thought because of--

627
00:29:34.314 --> 00:29:38.526
Iowa is significant
as a swing state

628
00:29:38.610 --> 00:29:41.321
and because of
the young leaders

629
00:29:41.404 --> 00:29:42.781
who just got elected
in the capital.

630
00:29:42.822 --> 00:29:44.324
we thought it would be
a good time

631
00:29:44.407 --> 00:29:47.869
to come here to Iowa
and see what's going on.

632
00:29:54.250 --> 00:29:56.336
The next project
is a program designed

633
00:29:56.377 --> 00:29:59.172
to have bipartisan colleagues
come together.

634
00:29:59.214 --> 00:30:00.590
have meaningful conversations.

635
00:30:00.673 --> 00:30:03.259
And I'm very grateful
that this future caucus

636
00:30:03.343 --> 00:30:04.552
has been established.

637
00:30:04.636 --> 00:30:05.553
With that. I want to make sure

638
00:30:05.637 --> 00:30:09.641
that we welcome Steven Olikara.

639
00:30:09.682 --> 00:30:12.310
the Millennial Action Project
president.

640
00:30:12.352 --> 00:30:14.896
(applause)

641
00:30:19.442 --> 00:30:21.236
What wows me when I'm in
the state capital

642
00:30:21.319 --> 00:30:23.279
is that we have
so many young legislators

643
00:30:23.363 --> 00:30:26.157
who are uniting
across party lines.

644
00:30:26.199 --> 00:30:27.826
They're legislators...

645
00:30:27.867 --> 00:30:29.369
So it's become a movement.

646
00:30:29.410 --> 00:30:32.372
Youngest representative.
youngest senator.

647
00:30:32.455 --> 00:30:33.957
You know. we want
to change politics.

648
00:30:34.040 --> 00:30:35.416
Probably going to be
the younger leaders

649
00:30:35.500 --> 00:30:37.544
who change it. so. actually.
you'll now be invited

650
00:30:37.585 --> 00:30:38.837
to our annual conference.

651
00:30:38.878 --> 00:30:39.712
Okay. Sometimes. like.

652
00:30:39.796 --> 00:30:41.422
with different caucuses
and stuff.

653
00:30:41.506 --> 00:30:43.174
I get a little weary
because they might be--

654
00:30:43.216 --> 00:30:44.634
slide to one side
or the other.

655
00:30:44.717 --> 00:30:48.221
but. yeah. I gotta talk
to leadership about it first.

656
00:30:48.304 --> 00:30:49.722
Yeah.

657
00:30:49.764 --> 00:30:52.600
I had a lot of people tell me
we would never get

658
00:30:52.684 --> 00:30:54.894
Democratic members
and Republican members

659
00:30:54.978 --> 00:30:57.772
to actually sign on.

660
00:30:57.856 --> 00:31:01.568
♪

661
00:31:01.651 --> 00:31:04.487
I remember Steven
actually talking to me

662
00:31:04.571 --> 00:31:06.990
back in 2014. 2015.

663
00:31:07.073 --> 00:31:08.867
when MAP was still just an idea.

664
00:31:08.908 --> 00:31:11.703
this kind of bipartisan
talking across the aisle.

665
00:31:11.744 --> 00:31:13.329
and I wasn't sure
if I thought it was

666
00:31:13.413 --> 00:31:14.706
something that would
actually work.

667
00:31:14.747 --> 00:31:16.499
You know. we were both
pretty young. right?

668
00:31:16.583 --> 00:31:18.585
I mean. you were
a year or two out of...

669
00:31:18.626 --> 00:31:20.503
We were going
against the grain

670
00:31:20.587 --> 00:31:25.592
by seeking credibility
on both sides of the aisle.

671
00:31:25.633 --> 00:31:27.927
♪

672
00:31:27.969 --> 00:31:32.724
That goes against virtually
everything in politics.

673
00:31:32.765 --> 00:31:33.933
♪

674
00:31:33.975 --> 00:31:35.977
People immediately dismiss us
and say.

675
00:31:36.060 --> 00:31:37.729
"Oh. they're just a bunch
of millennials.

676
00:31:37.770 --> 00:31:40.064
They don't really know
what they're doing."

677
00:31:40.106 --> 00:31:41.900
♪

678
00:31:41.941 --> 00:31:44.152
Yeah. there was a lot
of discouragement. right?

679
00:31:44.235 --> 00:31:45.570
-Yeah.
-Yeah. especially

680
00:31:45.612 --> 00:31:48.031
with people telling him
that he's going to have

681
00:31:48.114 --> 00:31:52.076
a hard time convincing people
to work together.

682
00:31:52.118 --> 00:31:53.995
You know. at the end of the day.

683
00:31:54.078 --> 00:31:57.457
you have to do something
which you really enjoy.

684
00:31:57.498 --> 00:32:01.044
When you die.
you have to look back and say.

685
00:32:01.127 --> 00:32:03.880
"Did I have a good life?"

686
00:32:03.963 --> 00:32:09.636
♪

687
00:32:09.719 --> 00:32:12.889
We are in Montgomery. Alabama.

688
00:32:12.972 --> 00:32:14.766
Slidell. Louisiana.

689
00:32:14.807 --> 00:32:15.850
Georgia!

690
00:32:15.934 --> 00:32:17.185
I'm standing in front
of the first

691
00:32:17.268 --> 00:32:19.312
White House of the Confederacy.

692
00:32:19.395 --> 00:32:21.189
We thought that this journey
was gonna be

693
00:32:21.272 --> 00:32:22.607
about bringing people together.

694
00:32:22.649 --> 00:32:24.817
I don't think we factored in
the impact

695
00:32:24.859 --> 00:32:27.028
that these stories
would have on us.

696
00:32:27.111 --> 00:32:30.031
Would you say that
there are African Americans

697
00:32:30.114 --> 00:32:32.867
who are not familiar
with the full history?

698
00:32:32.951 --> 00:32:34.702
There aren't
history books written

699
00:32:34.786 --> 00:32:37.330
that capture these realities.

700
00:32:37.372 --> 00:32:39.624
We love Arkansas!

701
00:32:39.666 --> 00:32:41.709
South Carolina. North Carolina.

702
00:32:41.793 --> 00:32:46.047
I could not get past
this racial divide.

703
00:32:46.130 --> 00:32:49.384
You have to make your life
less comfortable

704
00:32:49.467 --> 00:32:51.552
to understand the experience

705
00:32:51.636 --> 00:32:54.180
that people of color
are going through.

706
00:32:54.222 --> 00:32:55.056
Louisville!

707
00:32:55.139 --> 00:32:57.141
Wichita. Kansas.

708
00:32:57.183 --> 00:32:59.936
Welcome to Wyoming.

709
00:33:00.019 --> 00:33:01.020
Bozeman. Montana.

710
00:33:01.062 --> 00:33:03.648
on the way
to the Donald Trump rally.

711
00:33:03.690 --> 00:33:07.527
And I was a Trump supporter.
and in Jeff.

712
00:33:07.568 --> 00:33:09.529
I mean. he just about
didn't let me in his house.

713
00:33:09.570 --> 00:33:10.947
He was just like. "Pfft."

714
00:33:11.030 --> 00:33:13.116
(shouting)

715
00:33:13.199 --> 00:33:16.786
This one person in particular
works for an organization

716
00:33:16.869 --> 00:33:19.872
that my whole
professional career

717
00:33:19.956 --> 00:33:22.667
has fought against them
as a real enemy.

718
00:33:22.709 --> 00:33:25.211
I'm raising money
for a good cause.

719
00:33:25.294 --> 00:33:28.673
making sure people get
healthcare that they need.

720
00:33:28.715 --> 00:33:31.009
I didn't know
this was your house!

721
00:33:31.050 --> 00:33:33.678
-Happy Easter!
-Okay. let's go get eggs.

722
00:33:33.720 --> 00:33:35.638
It was cool to see
our kids begin

723
00:33:35.722 --> 00:33:39.392
to wrap their minds
around injustice.

724
00:33:39.434 --> 00:33:40.727
♪ To you ♪♪

725
00:33:40.768 --> 00:33:43.563
To break it down
to the simplest thing.

726
00:33:43.604 --> 00:33:45.732
-it's not fair.
-I originally thought

727
00:33:45.773 --> 00:33:48.026
I wasn't gonna be able to work
'cause I have autism

728
00:33:48.067 --> 00:33:50.194
and it makes it harder for me
to get a job.

729
00:33:50.236 --> 00:33:52.530
I mean. the way I see it.
everyone has challenges.

730
00:33:52.572 --> 00:33:55.825
You can either let it
put you down

731
00:33:55.908 --> 00:33:57.577
or you can find
the bright side.

732
00:33:57.660 --> 00:34:00.413
I expected to find an enemy.

733
00:34:00.455 --> 00:34:03.958
Instead. I found
a family member.

734
00:34:04.042 --> 00:34:08.671
♪

735
00:34:08.755 --> 00:34:11.883
Our daughter. Grace.
is six years old.

736
00:34:11.924 --> 00:34:15.094
and the day that she was born

737
00:34:15.136 --> 00:34:19.265
was one of the happiest.
toughest days of our lives.

738
00:34:19.348 --> 00:34:22.435
Neither of us had ever met
a person with Down syndrome

739
00:34:22.518 --> 00:34:24.020
until that day.

740
00:34:24.103 --> 00:34:26.355
Grace has changed the way
that I look at the world

741
00:34:26.439 --> 00:34:28.316
and look at other people.

742
00:34:28.399 --> 00:34:33.613
and that is a gift
that hardly anybody can give.

743
00:34:33.696 --> 00:34:37.408
It causes me to look
at other people with hope

744
00:34:37.450 --> 00:34:38.659
and not prejudgment

745
00:34:38.743 --> 00:34:40.286
because what you see
on the surface

746
00:34:40.369 --> 00:34:44.582
is not always
what is within somebody.

747
00:34:44.624 --> 00:34:47.043
She broke down the belief

748
00:34:47.126 --> 00:34:51.631
that certain people have
more value than others.

749
00:34:51.672 --> 00:34:53.466
and that started us
on a journey

750
00:34:53.508 --> 00:34:56.135
that we're on to this day.

751
00:34:56.177 --> 00:35:06.145
♪

752
00:35:21.994 --> 00:35:24.831
-Hi. How are you guys?
