00:36:31.480 --> 00:36:33.983
♪

788
00:36:34.066 --> 00:36:36.694
So alcohol is illegal
on the reservation?

789
00:36:36.736 --> 00:36:38.029
This is a dry reservation.

790
00:36:38.070 --> 00:36:39.363
You know. I might be
a friendly guy.

791
00:36:39.405 --> 00:36:42.742
I might be. you know.
taught well by my parents.

792
00:36:42.825 --> 00:36:45.203
but there are things
that anger me. right?

793
00:36:45.244 --> 00:36:49.624
And when you hurt my people.
it really bothers me.

794
00:36:49.707 --> 00:36:51.667
Well. sometimes anger is okay.

795
00:36:51.751 --> 00:36:55.171
Yeah. righteous anger.
you know?

796
00:36:55.254 --> 00:36:56.297
♪

797
00:36:56.380 --> 00:36:57.465
Hey. guys.

798
00:36:57.548 --> 00:36:58.758
How's it going? How's it going?

799
00:36:58.799 --> 00:36:59.759
All right. all right.

800
00:36:59.842 --> 00:37:02.929
Yeah. You want some coffee?

801
00:37:03.012 --> 00:37:04.805
-So are you Navajo?
-Yeah.

802
00:37:04.889 --> 00:37:06.974
What's one thing
you would want to tell people

803
00:37:07.058 --> 00:37:08.768
to help them understand
what life is like

804
00:37:08.851 --> 00:37:09.936
on the reservation?

805
00:37:09.977 --> 00:37:12.230
It's like Third World.

806
00:37:12.271 --> 00:37:14.941
Some places. it's like
a Third World country

807
00:37:14.982 --> 00:37:19.487
with no jobs here.
no opportunities.

808
00:37:19.570 --> 00:37:21.489
It's depressing
living on a reservation.

809
00:37:21.572 --> 00:37:23.157
There's no auto parts store.

810
00:37:23.241 --> 00:37:26.410
There's no cafe that you can
go and meet and have coffee.

811
00:37:26.452 --> 00:37:29.747
There are thousands of mines
across this landscape.

812
00:37:29.789 --> 00:37:33.209
uranium mines
never paid us a dime for.

813
00:37:33.292 --> 00:37:35.920
never closed it up
and capped it.

814
00:37:35.962 --> 00:37:38.339
That's our reward
for being Native American!

815
00:37:38.422 --> 00:37:42.510
We get uranium. we get murder.
we get alcohol!

816
00:37:42.593 --> 00:37:46.389
Nobody is doing
nothing about it!

817
00:37:46.472 --> 00:37:47.682
I used to serve a lot of people

818
00:37:47.765 --> 00:37:49.141
on the east side of Shiprock.

819
00:37:49.225 --> 00:37:52.311
He dropped his 40.
he turned around to pick it up

820
00:37:52.395 --> 00:37:54.647
and a swift truck hit him
pretty quick.

821
00:37:54.730 --> 00:37:55.815
Killed him instantly.

822
00:37:55.856 --> 00:37:56.816
Floyd is gone.

823
00:37:56.899 --> 00:37:59.026
And every day I go by at 9:30

824
00:37:59.110 --> 00:38:01.195
and I still look for them.

825
00:38:01.279 --> 00:38:03.364
I still look to see
if they're over there.

826
00:38:03.447 --> 00:38:05.241
see if they're hungry.

827
00:38:05.324 --> 00:38:08.077
You know. I love them
like a brother would.

828
00:38:08.160 --> 00:38:12.248
And when they go home.
yeah. it takes a part of me.

829
00:38:15.001 --> 00:38:19.547
Maybe there's these problems
with poverty and alcoholism

830
00:38:19.630 --> 00:38:23.175
because our government

831
00:38:23.217 --> 00:38:26.804
forcibly took them
off their land.

832
00:38:26.846 --> 00:38:28.764
removed their homes from them.

833
00:38:28.848 --> 00:38:31.726
punished them
for speaking their language.

834
00:38:31.809 --> 00:38:33.644
ripped families apart.

835
00:38:33.686 --> 00:38:36.022
You know. so I feel like
I have now a context

836
00:38:36.063 --> 00:38:39.275
of why there's brokenness

837
00:38:39.358 --> 00:38:42.445
and that has led
to how things are today.

838
00:38:42.528 --> 00:38:46.324
Our history is so much more
dark and complex

839
00:38:46.365 --> 00:38:49.201
than this. like. fairy tale
that we're taught.

840
00:38:49.243 --> 00:38:53.706
So we have to reconcile
that being an American

841
00:38:53.789 --> 00:38:54.999
for one person is not the same

842
00:38:55.041 --> 00:38:57.001
as being an American
for another.

843
00:38:57.043 --> 00:39:00.046
The great line
in our founding documents.

844
00:39:00.087 --> 00:39:02.631
"We the People" did not mean
"all the people."

845
00:39:02.715 --> 00:39:04.967
Policy cannot
accomplish something

846
00:39:05.051 --> 00:39:07.428
that can only happen
in a human heart.

847
00:39:07.511 --> 00:39:11.098
We've never been a place
where all men are created equal.

848
00:39:11.182 --> 00:39:12.224
but we could be.

849
00:39:12.308 --> 00:39:15.728
Now that we have this.
how do we use this

850
00:39:15.811 --> 00:39:17.730
in a constructive way?

851
00:39:17.813 --> 00:39:19.023
♪

852
00:39:19.065 --> 00:39:20.941
When I gave birth
to my third child.

853
00:39:21.025 --> 00:39:23.778
there were probably 15 doctors
in the room.

854
00:39:23.861 --> 00:39:25.821
The full power
of American medicine

855
00:39:25.905 --> 00:39:27.656
was behind that delivery.

856
00:39:27.740 --> 00:39:30.368
And Mechelle.
she deserved that

857
00:39:30.409 --> 00:39:32.244
and she didn't get it.

858
00:39:32.286 --> 00:39:34.497
That day was a turning point
in my life

859
00:39:34.580 --> 00:39:37.500
when I began to understand
for the first time

860
00:39:37.583 --> 00:39:41.128
why you need to say something
like. "Black Lives Matter."

861
00:39:41.212 --> 00:39:43.089
In my life
previous to that moment.

862
00:39:43.130 --> 00:39:45.383
I didn't understand
why it needed to be said.

863
00:39:45.424 --> 00:39:48.803
I thought. "Isn't it obvious
that everyone's life matters?"

864
00:39:48.886 --> 00:39:52.348
And the answer is. no.
it's not obvious.

865
00:39:52.431 --> 00:39:55.976
And it became clear to me
that day why it's so important

866
00:39:56.060 --> 00:39:58.646
that we. as her white brothers
and sisters.

867
00:39:58.729 --> 00:40:01.357
come into agreement
with the fact

868
00:40:01.440 --> 00:40:04.485
that her life matters
and her baby's life mattered.

869
00:40:04.568 --> 00:40:06.112
How horrible is that?

870
00:40:06.153 --> 00:40:09.115
We don't want more or better
or different attention

871
00:40:09.156 --> 00:40:11.283
than someone else
with a different color skin.

872
00:40:11.367 --> 00:40:13.619
That's not what America
is supposed to be.

873
00:40:13.702 --> 00:40:17.540
So if you're shining a light
on these stories.

874
00:40:17.623 --> 00:40:20.209
then hallelujah.
it's gonna make us better.

875
00:40:20.292 --> 00:40:23.963
I realized that something
was shifting inside of me.

876
00:40:24.046 --> 00:40:27.133
and I wasn't becoming
a Democrat.

877
00:40:27.174 --> 00:40:28.634
That's not what was happening.

878
00:40:28.717 --> 00:40:30.511
Which has been a big fear
for a lot of our friends.

879
00:40:30.594 --> 00:40:32.471
"Oh. no. you guys are
becoming Democrats."

880
00:40:32.555 --> 00:40:36.267
It was--it was stepping
into someone's story. okay?

881
00:40:36.308 --> 00:40:38.644
And that's different. that has
nothing to do with politics.

882
00:40:38.686 --> 00:40:42.731
Yeah. You know. so I think
we learned that racism

883
00:40:42.815 --> 00:40:46.485
has been a thing in the past
for a long time. but. to me.

884
00:40:46.527 --> 00:40:48.320
I kind of thought that was over.

885
00:40:48.404 --> 00:40:49.989
I thought with
the Voting Rights Act.

886
00:40:50.072 --> 00:40:52.074
Civil Rights Act.
amend. get over it.

887
00:40:52.158 --> 00:40:53.576
These are just
small little things.

888
00:40:53.659 --> 00:40:56.620
but we saw how it manifests
still today

889
00:40:56.662 --> 00:40:59.582
in our communities.
and it was shocking to us.

890
00:40:59.665 --> 00:41:01.500
When did prayer come involved?

891
00:41:01.542 --> 00:41:02.835
How much does God matter

892
00:41:02.918 --> 00:41:05.337
in terms of what
you're doing together?

893
00:41:05.379 --> 00:41:08.966
And how would you. you know.
you can be candid with us.

894
00:41:09.008 --> 00:41:10.384
who is God to you?

895
00:41:10.468 --> 00:41:13.012
I don't want to impose
my faith on others.

896
00:41:13.095 --> 00:41:16.891
but. for us. God is everything.

897
00:41:16.974 --> 00:41:18.267
I'm gonna push back
just a little bit.

898
00:41:18.350 --> 00:41:21.437
-Yeah.
-Um. you began with the premise

899
00:41:21.520 --> 00:41:24.857
that things are broken.
but would you agree

900
00:41:24.899 --> 00:41:27.151
that not everyone agrees
on what is broken?

901
00:41:27.193 --> 00:41:28.986
-Of course. yeah.
-There are a lot of people

902
00:41:29.028 --> 00:41:30.863
who'd say. "Well.
politics isn't designed

903
00:41:30.905 --> 00:41:32.364
to solve all these problems

904
00:41:32.406 --> 00:41:33.908
that you've talked
about tonight."

905
00:41:33.991 --> 00:41:35.701
But we want to share
these stories

906
00:41:35.743 --> 00:41:37.119
with the people from our world

907
00:41:37.203 --> 00:41:38.746
who don't know
that there's a problem.

908
00:41:38.829 --> 00:41:41.499
But I think the hard part
is to talk about these things

909
00:41:41.540 --> 00:41:44.460
in platitudes. because I think
every one of us would say.

910
00:41:44.543 --> 00:41:46.795
"Yeah. there are things
that are broken."

911
00:41:46.879 --> 00:41:48.422
but we wouldn't
necessarily agree

912
00:41:48.506 --> 00:41:51.050
with what they are
and what the solution is.

913
00:41:51.133 --> 00:41:53.302
I've seen a level of brokenness
in this country

914
00:41:53.385 --> 00:41:55.179
that you haven't seen.
and you've seen a level

915
00:41:55.221 --> 00:41:57.389
of unbrokenness
that I haven't seen.

916
00:41:57.473 --> 00:41:59.934
And that's why
it's super difficult

917
00:42:00.017 --> 00:42:02.895
to get everyone. as you say.
to do this thing

918
00:42:02.978 --> 00:42:04.230
that's reconciliation.

919
00:42:04.313 --> 00:42:07.316
I guess part of it
is kind of me thinking.

920
00:42:07.399 --> 00:42:09.610
I wonder if
it's even possible.

921
00:42:09.693 --> 00:42:11.904
I don't know if it's possible.

922
00:42:11.946 --> 00:42:22.081
♪

923
00:42:30.005 --> 00:42:31.257
If you look very closely.
you can see

924
00:42:31.298 --> 00:42:34.051
that her ear is kind of closed.

925
00:42:34.093 --> 00:42:38.264
When Heather was born.
she only had one ear open.

926
00:42:38.347 --> 00:42:41.350
That encouraged her
to be more recognizing

927
00:42:41.433 --> 00:42:44.228
of people being treated
unfairly.

928
00:42:45.437 --> 00:42:49.525
I learned a lot from her
over the years.

929
00:42:49.608 --> 00:42:52.611
I was struggling to understand
white privilege

930
00:42:52.653 --> 00:42:55.114
'cause I thought.
"My parents and I worked

931
00:42:55.155 --> 00:42:57.283
for everything we got."

932
00:42:57.324 --> 00:43:01.453
My kids grew up being called
"trailer trash."

933
00:43:01.495 --> 00:43:04.331
but that's not what
white privilege is about.

934
00:43:06.625 --> 00:43:09.169
(engine puttering)

935
00:43:13.966 --> 00:43:18.012
Your daughter was fighting
the real fight. was she not?

936
00:43:18.095 --> 00:43:20.639
And you taught her that.

937
00:43:20.681 --> 00:43:24.101
And so. here in Cleveland.
the same thing is going on.

938
00:43:24.143 --> 00:43:26.979
because it is when things
like this happen

939
00:43:27.062 --> 00:43:29.148
that we see the true power.

940
00:43:29.231 --> 00:43:31.692
It was an incident
that happened that...

941
00:43:33.110 --> 00:43:35.487
It really screwed
with our lives.

942
00:43:35.571 --> 00:43:37.823
I'm trying not to get
emotional. I'm sorry.

943
00:43:37.865 --> 00:43:39.366
My 15-year-old sister.

944
00:43:39.450 --> 00:43:42.494
she was jumped
at busted her teeth.

945
00:43:42.536 --> 00:43:44.830
I tell my mom
to call the police.

946
00:43:44.913 --> 00:43:46.206
Make a police report

947
00:43:46.290 --> 00:43:47.666
'cause that's all we can do.

948
00:43:47.750 --> 00:43:50.628
My mom tried everything.
doin' it the right way.

949
00:43:50.669 --> 00:43:53.797
and we got charged
with felony two.

950
00:43:53.839 --> 00:43:55.341
Oh!

951
00:43:55.382 --> 00:43:57.760
It's a hard struggle.

952
00:43:57.843 --> 00:43:59.428
Um. a couple of things.

953
00:43:59.511 --> 00:44:02.598
I wear today Angelo Miller.

954
00:44:02.681 --> 00:44:05.684
Angelo Miller
was killed by police.

955
00:44:05.768 --> 00:44:08.562
and I wanna say I thank you

956
00:44:08.646 --> 00:44:09.688
for standing up

957
00:44:09.730 --> 00:44:12.107
for people who can't
stand up for themselves.

958
00:44:12.191 --> 00:44:13.150
-Amen!
-I just wanted

959
00:44:13.192 --> 00:44:15.110
to come here and say that.

960
00:44:15.194 --> 00:44:17.696
What I hear from you guys.
unfortunately.

961
00:44:17.738 --> 00:44:19.198
I hear a lot of places.

962
00:44:19.281 --> 00:44:21.241
And believe it or not.
there are still a lot of people

963
00:44:21.325 --> 00:44:23.494
who would never
believe your story.

964
00:44:23.535 --> 00:44:26.497
I know your story is true.
I have heard that story

965
00:44:26.538 --> 00:44:29.041
in so many places
across the country.

966
00:44:29.083 --> 00:44:32.252
So. we have a lot of work to do.

967
00:44:32.336 --> 00:44:33.879
Thank you so much.

968
00:44:33.962 --> 00:44:36.423
(applause)

969
00:44:36.507 --> 00:44:38.300
A lot of people think that

970
00:44:38.384 --> 00:44:41.387
there are no
racial issues whatsoever.

971
00:44:41.428 --> 00:44:44.556
Why are we treating
people unequally?

972
00:44:44.598 --> 00:44:45.766
Thank you.

973
00:44:47.935 --> 00:44:49.228
When any of us is marginalized.

974
00:44:49.311 --> 00:44:51.772
-we are all marginalized.
-That's right.

975
00:44:51.855 --> 00:44:53.565
That's right.

976
00:44:53.649 --> 00:44:55.693
Part of the reason
I do what I do

977
00:44:55.734 --> 00:44:59.029
is because parents
are losing their kids

978
00:44:59.071 --> 00:45:02.449
in tragic circumstances
all the time.

979
00:45:02.533 --> 00:45:04.785
That's what I'm
trying to prevent.

980
00:45:08.247 --> 00:45:10.040
-Rob!
-Susan!

981
00:45:10.082 --> 00:45:11.959
What's your
official title now?

982
00:45:12.042 --> 00:45:14.837
I'm a professor. so. um.

983
00:45:14.920 --> 00:45:16.255
they call me Professor Lee.

984
00:45:16.338 --> 00:45:19.258
I just go by Rob most days.

985
00:45:19.299 --> 00:45:21.468
It is my distinct privilege

986
00:45:21.552 --> 00:45:24.471
to introduce to you Susan Bro.

987
00:45:24.555 --> 00:45:27.433
When I met Susan.
she came up to me.

988
00:45:27.474 --> 00:45:30.018
gave me this huge hug

989
00:45:30.102 --> 00:45:32.271
that I didn't deserve.

990
00:45:32.312 --> 00:45:33.814
and I apologized to her

991
00:45:33.897 --> 00:45:38.485
because my ancestry has been
filled with hate and racism.

992
00:45:38.569 --> 00:45:41.029
The statue of my ancestor
was the reason

993
00:45:41.113 --> 00:45:44.575
that many people were
marching on Charlottesville.

994
00:45:44.616 --> 00:45:46.201
Susan looked at me.
and she said.

995
00:45:46.285 --> 00:45:48.287
"Don't apologize.

996
00:45:48.328 --> 00:45:51.039
Do something about it."

997
00:45:51.123 --> 00:45:53.625
(applause)

998
00:45:54.835 --> 00:45:55.919
Thank you. good morning.

999
00:45:55.961 --> 00:45:58.046
